completions.md
     1вЖТ# The completions command
     3вЖТThe completions command is used to generate auto-completions for some common shells.
     4вЖТThis means when you type `mdbook` in your shell, you can then press your shell's auto-complete key (usually the Tab key) and it may display what the valid options are, or finish partial input.
     5вЖТ
     6вЖТThe completions first need to be installed for your shell:
     7вЖТ
     8вЖТ```bash
     9вЖТ# bash
    10вЖТmdbook completions bash > ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/mdbook
    11вЖТ# oh-my-zsh
    12вЖТmdbook completions zsh > ~/.oh-my-zsh/completions/_mdbook
    13вЖТautoload -U compinit && compinit
    14вЖТ```
    15вЖТ
    16вЖТThe command prints a completion script for the given shell.
    17вЖТRun `mdbook completions --help` for a list of supported shells.
    18вЖТ
    19вЖТWhere to place the completions depend on which shell you are using and your operating system.
    20вЖТConsult your shell's documentation for more information one where to place the script.

init.md
     1вЖТ# The init command
     3вЖТThere is some minimal boilerplate that is the same for every new book. It's for
     4вЖТthis purpose that mdBook includes an `init` command.
     5вЖТ
     6вЖТThe `init` command is used like this:
     7вЖТ
     8вЖТ```bash
     9вЖТmdbook init
    10вЖТ```
    11вЖТ
    12вЖТWhen using the `init` command for the first time, a couple of files will be set
    13вЖТup for you:
    14вЖТ```bash
    15вЖТbook-test/
    16вЖТвФЬвФАвФА book
    17вЖТвФФвФАвФА src
    18вЖТ    вФЬвФАвФА chapter_1.md
    19вЖТ    вФФвФАвФА SUMMARY.md
    20вЖТ```
    21вЖТ
    22вЖТ- The `src` directory is where you write your book in markdown. It contains all
    23вЖТ  the source files, configuration files, etc.
    24вЖТ
    25вЖТ- The `book` directory is where your book is rendered. All the output is ready
    26вЖТ  to be uploaded to a server to be seen by your audience.
    27вЖТ
    28вЖТ- The `SUMMARY.md` is the skeleton of your
    29вЖТ  book, and is discussed in more detail [in another
    30вЖТ  chapter](../format/summary.md).
    31вЖТ
    32вЖТ#### Tip: Generate chapters from SUMMARY.md вА¶
    39вЖТ#### Specify a directory вА¶
    48вЖТ#### `--theme` вА¶
    56вЖТ#### `--title` вА¶
    65вЖТ#### `--ignore` вА¶
    80вЖТ#### `--force` вА¶

serve.md
     1вЖТ# The serve command
     3вЖТThe serve command is used to preview a book by serving it via HTTP at
     4вЖТ`localhost:3000` by default: 
     5вЖТ
     6вЖТ```bash
     7вЖТmdbook serve
     8вЖТ```
     9вЖТ
    10вЖТThe `serve` command  watches the book's `src` directory for
    11вЖТchanges, rebuilding the book and refreshing clients for each change; this includes
    12вЖТre-creating deleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`! A websocket
    13вЖТconnection is used to trigger the client-side refresh.
    14вЖТ
    15вЖТ***Note:*** *The `serve` command is for testing a book's HTML output, and is not
    16вЖТintended to be a complete HTTP server for a website.*
    17вЖТ
    18вЖТ#### Specify a directory вА¶
    27вЖТ### Server options
    29вЖТThe `serve` hostname defaults to `localhost`, and the port defaults to `3000`. Either option can be specified on the command line:
    30вЖТ
    31вЖТ```bash
    32вЖТmdbook serve path/to/book -p 8000 -n 127.0.0.1 
    33вЖТ```
    34вЖТ
    35вЖТ#### `--open` вА¶
    40вЖТ#### `--dest-dir` вА¶
    49вЖТ#### Specify exclude patterns вА¶

test.md
     1вЖТ# The test command
     3вЖТWhen writing a book, you sometimes need to automate some tests. For example,
     4вЖТ[The Rust Programming Book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/book/) uses a lot
     5вЖТof code examples that could get outdated. Therefore it is very important for
     6вЖТthem to be able to automatically test these code examples.
     7вЖТ
     8вЖТmdBook supports a `test` command that will run all available tests in a book. At
     9вЖТthe moment, only Rust tests are supported.
    10вЖТ
    11вЖТ#### Disable tests on a code block вА¶
    31вЖТ#### Specify a directory вА¶
    40вЖТ#### `--library-path` вА¶
    57вЖТ#### `--chapter` вА¶

watch.md
     1вЖТ# The watch command
     3вЖТThe `watch` command is useful when you want your book to be rendered on every
     4вЖТfile change. You could repeatedly issue `mdbook build` every time a file is
     5вЖТchanged. But using `mdbook watch` once will watch your files and will trigger a
     6вЖТbuild automatically whenever you modify a file; this includes re-creating
     7вЖТdeleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`!
     8вЖТ
     9вЖТ#### Specify a directory вА¶
    18вЖТ#### `--open` вА¶
    23вЖТ#### `--dest-dir` вА¶
    32вЖТ#### Specify exclude patterns вА¶
